name1                    = '''Bishan-Toa Payoh GRC'''\n{{Bulleted list|list_style=line-height: inherit; | [[Chee Hong Tat]] | Chong Kee Hiong | [[Josephine Teo]] }}\n| area_footnotes                  = <ref name=citypopulation>\n{{Cite web |url=http://www.citypopulation.de/php/singapore-admin.php?adm1id=101 |title=City Population - statistics, maps and charts - Bishan |access-date=30 December 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151206121810/http://www.citypopulation.de/php/singapore-admin.php?adm1id=101 |archive-date=6 December 2015 |url-status=live |df=dmy-all }}\n</ref><ref name=HDBstatistics>\n{{Cite web |url=http://www10.hdb.gov.sg/ebook/ar2015/html5/index.html?opf=tablet%2FKey%20Statistics.xml |title=HDB Key Statistics FY 2014/2015 |access-date=21 July 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304145846/http://www10.hdb.gov.sg/ebook/ar2015/html5/index.html?opf=tablet%2FKey%20Statistics.xml |archive-date=4 March 2016 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}  {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304145846/http://www10.hdb.gov.sg/ebook/ar2015/html5/index.html?opf=tablet%2FKey%20Statistics.xml |date=4 March 2016  }}\n</ref>\n| area_total_km2                  = 7.62\n| area_blank1_title               = Residential\n| area_blank1_km2                 = 1.72\n| area_rank                       = 38th\n| population_as_of                = 2019\n| population_footnotes            = <ref name=citypopulation/><ref name=HDBstatistics/><ref name=singstat>\n{{cite website|url=https://www.singstat.gov.sg/find-data/search-by-theme/population/geographic-distribution/latest-data|title=Statistics Singapore - Geographic Distribution - 2018 Latest Data|accessdate=February 11, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160130111952/http://www.singstat.gov.sg/docs/default-source/default-document-library/statistics/browse_by_theme/population/statistical_tables/tablea12-2000-2015.xls|archive-date=30 January 2016|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}\n</ref>\n| population_total                = 88,010\n| population_density_km2          = auto\n| population_rank                 = 22nd\n| population_density_rank         = 15th\n| population_demonym              = '''Official'''\n* Bishan resident\n'''Colloquial'''\n* Bishaner\n* Bishanian\n* Bishanite\n| demographics1_footnotes         = <ref name=singstat/>\n| demographics_type1              = Ethnic groups\n| demographics1_title1            = [[Chinese Singaporeans|Chinese]]\n| demographics1_info1             = 77,220\n| demographics1_title2            = [[Malay Singaporeans|Malays]]\n| demographics1_info2             = 3,760\n| demographics1_title3            = [[Indian Singaporeans|Indians]]\n| demographics1_info3             = 7,000\n| demographics1_title4            = Others\n| demographics1_info4             = 2,720\n| postal_code_type                = Postal district\n| postal_code                     = 20\n| blank_name_sec1                 = Dwelling units\n| blank_info_sec1                 = 19,664\n| blank1_name_sec1                = Projected ultimate\n| blank1_info_sec1                = 34,000\n| official_name                   = \n}}\n\n'''Bishan''' {{IPAc-en|b|\u026a|\u0283|\u028c|n}}, also known as either '''Bishan New Town''' or '''Bishan Town''', is a [[Planning Areas of Singapore|planning area]] and [[New towns of Singapore|matured residential town]] located at the northernmost portion of the [[Central Region, Singapore|Central Region]] of [[Singapore]]. Statistically, the area is ranked the 38th biggest in terms of geographical size and the 22nd most populated planning area in the country. It is located at the most Central point of Singapore, and is made out of Upper Thomson, Marymount, Shunfu, Sin Ming, Bishan North and Bishan East. There are also many private residential properties in Bishan.<ref name=singstat/> This however, makes Bishan ranked 15th in terms of population density.<ref name=citypopulation/> Apart from its boundary with the [[Central Catchment Nature Reserve|Central Water Catchment]] in the west, Bishan borders three other planning areas - [[Ang Mo Kio]] to the north, [[Toa Payoh]] to the south and [[Serangoon]] to the east.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.singstat.gov.sg/docs/default-source/default-document-library/publications/publications_and_papers/population_and_population_structure/population2014-map1.pdf|title=STATISTICS SINGAPORE - Map of Planning Areas/Subzones in Singapore|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150408052357/https://www.singstat.gov.sg/docs/default-source/default-document-library/publications/publications_and_papers/population_and_population_structure/population2014-map1.pdf|archive-date=8 April 2015|url-status=dead|access-date=30 March 2016}}</ref>\n\nWhat is now Bishan today was once land that belonged to [[Singapore Kwong Wai Siew Peck San Theng|Kwong Wai Siew Peck San Theng]], a cemetery that mainly served the [[Cantonese people|Cantonese]] and [[Hakka people|Hakka]] communities of Singapore. Following the establishment of the cemetery in 1870, the first human settlements began to appear in the area, forming what eventually became Kampong San Teng.<ref name=\"infopedia\"/><ref name=HeritageTrailPST>\n{{cite book|title=Bishan Heritage Trail|url=https://www.ura.gov.sg/~/media/User%20Defined/URA%20Online/publications/research-resources/walking-maps-trails/Pdfs/Bishan%20Trail%20Map.pdf|author=[[Singapore Kwong Wai Siew Peck San Theng]]|access-date=30 March 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160412083520/https://www.ura.gov.sg/~/media/User%20Defined/URA%20Online/publications/research-resources/walking-maps-trails/Pdfs/Bishan%20Trail%20Map.pdf|archive-date=12 April 2016|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}\n</ref> During the [[Battle of Singapore]] in 1942, Peck San Theng was the site of a fierce firefight between the invading Japanese forces and the defending British.<ref name=\"infopedia\"/><ref name=\"asiaone20150614\">\n{{cite news |author=Zhuo, Tee |title=Bishan was site of bloody WWII battle |url=http://news.asiaone.com/news/singapore/bishan-was-site-bloody-wwii-battle |newspaper=[[The Straits Times]] |location=Singapore |date=14 June 2015 |access-date=28 June 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150617010048/http://news.asiaone.com/news/singapore/bishan-was-site-bloody-wwii-battle |archive-date=17 June 2015 |url-status=live |df=dmy-all }}\n</ref> The subsequent [[Japanese occupation of Singapore|fall of the island to the Japanese]] that same year eventually made Peck San Theng a place of refuge for most of the Singapore population.<ref name=\"History\">{{cite web |url=http://bishanheritagetrail.sg/index.php/history/ |title=Bishan Heritage Trail: History |website=Bishan Heritage Trail project |date= |accessdate=2015-07-20 }}{{dead link|date=July 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> In 1973, Peck San Theng stopped accepting burials and six years later following a government lease, land was acquired for development.<ref>\n{{cite news|title=Govt acquires site for housing scheme to link Toa Payoh, Ang Mo Kio estates|url=http://eresources.nlb.gov.sg/newspapers/Digitised/Article/straitstimes19790430-1.2.47.aspx|date=30 April 1979|newspaper=[[The Straits Times]]|access-date=30 March 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160329210007/http://eresources.nlb.gov.sg/newspapers/Digitised/Article/straitstimes19790430-1.2.47.aspx|archive-date=29 March 2016|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}\n</ref> Graves were then exhumed between 1982 and 1984 paving the way for the construction of Bishan New Town in 1983.<ref name=\"infopedia\"/> Today, Peck San Theng still remains in operation, although it had since been converted into a [[columbarium]].\n\nBishan New Town became the first in Singapore to depart from the [[brutalist architecture|brutalist]] design seen in most previous [[Housing and Development Board]] (HDB) towns. Instead of slab-like residential blocks that were built in uniformed rows, apartment blocks in Bishan varied in height and were often dislocated. Flats within the town also featured [[Roof pitch|pitched roofs]] which have since become closely associated with the skyline of Bishan.<ref name=\"infopedia\"/><ref name=HeritageTrailPST/> The town is also home to three of Singapore's most prestigious educational institutions, [[Catholic High School, Singapore|Catholic High School]], [[Raffles Girls' School]] and [[Raffles Institution]].<ref name=HeritageTrailPST/><ref name=\"education\">{{cite web |url= http://bishanheritagetrail.sg/index.php/education/ |title= Bishan Heritage Trail: Education |website= Bishan Heritage Trail project |date=  |accessdate= 2015-07-17 }}{{dead link|date=July 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n\n==Etymology==\nBishan derived its name from the [[Cantonese language|Cantonese]] term for large [[burial ground]], ''Peck San Theng''  ({{zh|s=\u78a7\u5c71\u4ead|p=b\u00ecsh\u0101nt\u00edng}}), which literally translates as \"pavilions on the green\".<ref name=\"streetdirectory\">{{cite web |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20150629075822/http://www.streetdirectory.com/asia_travel/travel/travel_main.php?zonename=Bishan |archivedate= 2015-06-29 |url= http://www.streetdirectory.com/asia_travel/travel/travel_main.php?zonename=Bishan |title= Bishan District Guide |website = [[Streetdirectory.com]] | date = |accessdate= 2015-06-28}}</ref><ref>Victor R Savage, Brenda S A Yeoh (2003), ''Toponymics \u2013 A Study of Singapore Street Names'', Eastern Universities Press, {{ISBN|981-210-205-1}}</ref> This term reflects the neighbourhood's origins as a burial ground that was established in 1870 by [[Cantonese people|Cantonese]] and [[Hakka people|Hakka]] immigrants.<ref name=\"infopedia\"/> This burial ground has since been redeveloped and the original graves were relocated to the nearby [[Kwong Wai Siew Peck San Theng|Peck San Theng Temple]].<ref name=\"infopedia\"/>\n\n==Geography==\n\n===Bishan Planning Area===\nBishan Planning Area, as defined by Singapore's Urban Redevelopment Authority is situated in the Central Region of Singapore, bounded by planning areas of [[Ang Mo Kio]] to the north, [[Toa Payoh]] to the south and [[Serangoon]] to the east.\n\nBishan New Town sits within this planning area.\n\n====Subzones====\nBishan North Blocks 2XX\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n!Name of estates\n!Location\n!Notable structures\n!Accessibility\n|-\n\nBishan North Street 22, 23 and 24\n\n|Bishan East\n|Areas along Bishan Street 11, Bishan Street 12 and Bishan Street 13\n|[[Bishan MRT station]], [[Bishan Bus Interchange]], [[Bishan Community Library]], [[Junction 8 Shopping Centre]], [[Central Provident Fund]] Bishan Building, Bishan Neighbourhood Police Post, [[Bishan Stadium]], Bishan Swimming Complex, Bishan Sports Hall, [[Bishan Community Club]], [[Bishan Depot]], The Singapore Scout Association, Kuo Chuan Presbyterian Primary School, [[Kuo Chuan Presbyterian Secondary School]], Guangyang Primary School, [[Guangyang Secondary School]], [[Masjid An-Nahdhah]] and [[Ministry of Education, Singapore|Ministry of Education]] Language Centre (Bishan)\n|[[Bishan MRT station]] and buses\n|-\n|[[Marymount, Singapore|Marymount]]\n|Areas to the immediate west of Bishan Road\n|Shunfu HDBs, Wet Market, Hawker Centre [[Raffles Institution]], [[Catholic High School, Singapore|Catholic High School]], [[Whitley Secondary School]], [[Marymount MRT station]], [[Bishan-Ang Mo Kio Park]], \n|[[Marymount MRT station]] and buses\n|-\n|Upper Thomson\n|Western Bishan\n|[[Bishan-Ang Mo Kio Park]], Thomson Community Club, Bishan Fire Station, [[Sin Ming]], Peirce Secondary School as well as the future [[Bright Hill MRT station]] and [[Upper Thomson MRT station]]\n|Buses\n|}\n\n==History==\nPeck San Theng cemetery was established in 1870 on the site of present-day Bishan by [[Cantonese people|Cantonese]] and [[Hakka people|Hakka]] immigrants.<ref name=\"infopedia\"/> People began to settle around the cemetery, and Kampong San Theng and Soon Hock Village (which lay within Kampong San Theng grounds),<ref name=\"streetdirectory\" /> soon grew in size.<ref name=\"infopedia\" /> Singapore Kwong Wai Siew Peck San Theng, a federation of 16 Cantonese [[clan]]s in Singapore, managed and ran Kampong San Theng.<ref name=\"infopedia\" /> This settlement grew over time to accommodate nearly 2000 inhabitants at the beginning of the 20th century.<ref name=\"asiaone20150614\"/>\n\nDuring [[World War II]], the Peck San Theng cemetery became a battle ground between British and Japanese forces. The 2nd Battalion of the [[Cambridgeshire Regiment]] had engaged the Japanese forces on 14 February 1942 over the nearby strategically important [[Macritchie Reservoir]]. The Japanese also bombed Kampong San Teng, which resulted in significant civilian casualties. The battle ended the next day, 15 January,  when [[Battle of Singapore#Fall of Singapore|the British surrendered]] to the Japanese. At that point, British troops were still holding out along Braddell Road.<ref name=\"asiaone20150614\" /> During the [[Japanese Occupation of Singapore]], this area became a refuge for people trying to evade the Japanese because the Japanese occupiers were afraid to enter the cemetery.<ref name=\"History\"/>\n\nAfter the war, the graves of Peck San Theng became a known gangster hideout and gang-related crimes became rife in the area.<ref name=\"thestraitstimes19870813\">{{cite news |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |title= Spanking new Bishan has no identity problem |newspaper=[[The Straits Times]] |location= Singapore |date= 13 August 1987}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |title= Police Raid Lair, Seize Weapons |newspaper=[[The Straits Times]] |location= Singapore |date= 23 August 1960}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |title= Samsu gang crippled by Customs |url= |newspaper=New Nation |location= Singapore |date= 31 October 1974}}</ref> In 1973, the government ordered the cemetery to be closed and mandated that no fresh burials can be done within the cemetery.<ref>{{cite news |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |title= Century old cemetery ordered to close |newspaper=[[The Straits Times]] |location= Singapore |date= 14 September 1973}}</ref> The government later acquired this cemetery land from the Kwong Wai Siew Peck San Theng foundation for [[Singapore Dollar|SGD$]]$4.95 million in 1979.<ref name=\"straitstimes19790430\">{{cite news |author=Wee, Paul |title= Govt acquires site for housing scheme to link Toa Payoh, Ang Mo Kio estates |newspaper=[[The Straits Times]] |location= Singapore |date= 30 April 1979}}</ref><ref name=\"straitstimes19800611\">{{cite news |title= $4.9m compensation |newspaper=[[The Straits Times]] |location= Singapore |date= 11 June 1980}}</ref> As compensation, the government gave 3 hectares of the land back to the foundation for the foundation to build a [[columbarium]].<ref name=\"straitstimes19800611\" /> The foundation subsequently built a multi-story columbarium  complex on this land.<ref name=\"straitstimes19850429\">{{cite news |author= Leong Weng Kam |title= 'Condo' tor the dead |newspaper=[[The Straits Times]] |location= Singapore |date= 29 April 1985}}</ref>\n\nIn the early 1970s, the [[Housing Development Board]] (HDB) built the first housing estate which is located at Sin Ming Road along with clusters of industrial sectors. The first blocks of residential flats were numbered Block 22-26, now known as Sin Ming Ville. Sin Ming industrial estate is also known to be a popular destination for cars and vehicles related matters as the estate houses mainly workshops and establishments specialising in vehicle maintenance and registration.\n\nBy the 1980s, the [[Housing Development Board]] (HDB) had already begun further expanding the area into a satellite housing estate to meet the rising demand for housing from Singapore's then-growing population.<ref name=\"singaporemonitor19841013\">{{cite news |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |title= HDB prepares for challenges ahead |newspaper=Singapore Monitor |location= Singapore |date= 13 October 1984 }}</ref> The residents in Kampong San Teng were resettled and a mass exhumation of the 170,000 graves were carried out in 1980.<ref name=\"straitstimes19850528\">{{cite news |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |title= First few newly-built Bishan blocks snapped up |newspaper=[[The Straits Times]] |location= Singapore |date= 28 May 1985 }}</ref> Redevelopment of the area officially started in 1982.<ref name=\"infopedia\" /> On this land, HDB planned to construct 24,600 residential units distributed across 4 distinct neighbourhoods: Bishan East, Bishan North, Bishan West (subsequently renamed Sin Ming Garden Estate in 1988)<ref name=\"straitstimes19880417\">{{cite news |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |title= Bishan West's new name |newspaper=[[The Straits Times]] |location= Singapore |date= 17 April 1988 }}</ref> and Shunfu Estate, of which Bishan East will be the largest.<ref name=\"straitstimes19850528\" />\n\nThe first five blocks of housing units were completed by 1985.<ref name=\"straitstimes19850528\" /> There were initial fears of a poor demand for houses in Bishan as they had bad [[fengshui]] since they were built on a former cemetery.<ref name=\"streetdirectory\" /> However, the first batch of houses were all snapped out during their launch to buyers who were attracted by the central location of Bishan.<ref name=\"straitstimes19850528\" />\n\n==Sports==\n{{see also| Bishan Sports Hall | Bishan Stadium}}\n[[File:YOGArtisticGymnastics-BishanSportsHall-Singapore-20100816-14.JPG|thumb|Gymnastics competitions at the [[2010 Summer Youth Olympics]]]]\nBishan Sports Centre, formerly known as Bishan Sports and Recreation Centre, houses sporting facilities such as a [[Bishan Sports Hall|sports hall]], a [[Bishan Stadium|stadium]], a dance studio and a swimming complex.<ref name=\"timeoutsg\">{{cite magazine |url= http://www.timeout.com/singapore/sport-and-fitness/bishan-sports-centre |title= Bishan Sports Centre on Time Out Singapore |magazine = [[Time Out (magazine)|Time Out]] | date = 2015-03-10 |accessdate= 2015-07-05}}</ref> Managed by [[Sport Singapore]], these sporting facilities cater to both the general public and professional athletes.<ref name=\"activesg\">\n{{cite web |url= https://www.myactivesg.com/facilities/sports-recreation-centres/bishan-sports-recreation-centre |title= Bishan Sports Centre on Sports Singapore |website= Sports Singapore |accessdate= 2015-07-05 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20150705203334/https://www.myactivesg.com/facilities/sports-recreation-centres/bishan-sports-recreation-centre |archive-date= 5 July 2015 |url-status= dead |df= dmy-all }}\n</ref>\n\nSeveral major national and international level sporting events has been held at the Bishan Sports Centre, including the [[2009 Asian Youth Games]] and the [[2010 Youth Olympic Games]].<ref name=\"activesg\" /> Bishan Sports Hall, which serves as the primary venue for [[gymnastics]] competitions in Singapore,<ref name=\"timeoutsg\" /> has hosted gymnastic competitions as part of the [[2009 Asian Youth Games]],<ref>\n{{cite web |url= http://eresources.nlb.gov.sg/infopedia/articles/SIP_1574_2009-09-29.html |title= Asian Youth Games |website= National Library Board, Singapore |date= 2009-09-29 |accessdate= 2015-07-05 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20150706112420/http://eresources.nlb.gov.sg/infopedia/articles/SIP_1574_2009-09-29.html |archive-date= 6 July 2015 |url-status= live |df= dmy-all }}\n</ref> [[2010 Youth Olympic Games]]<ref name=\"yog\">{{cite web |url= http://app.msf.gov.sg/Portals/0/Summary/publication/SD/SYOG%202010%20Report%20Key%20Statistics.pdf |title= SYOG 2010 Report: Key Statistics |website= [[Ministry of Social and Family Development]] |date= 2009-09-29 |accessdate= 2015-07-05 }}{{Dead link|date=August 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> and the [[2015 SEA Games]].<ref name=\"st20150528\">\n{{cite web |url= http://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/road-closures-at-bishan-sports-centre-and-jalan-besar-stadium-during-sea-games |title= Road closures at Bishan Sports Centre and Jalan Besar Stadium during SEA Games |website= [[The Straits Times]] |date= 28 May 2015 |accessdate= 2015-07-05 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20150705104310/http://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/road-closures-at-bishan-sports-centre-and-jalan-besar-stadium-during-sea-games |archive-date= 5 July 2015 |url-status= live |df= dmy-all }}\n</ref> It is also the venue for national-level gymnastics competition in Singapore.<ref>\n{{cite web |url= http://yourhealth.asiaone.com/content/spore-national-gymnast-gruelling-schedule-keeps-her-shape |title= S'pore national gymnast on gruelling schedule that keeps her in shape |website= [[The Straits Times]] |publisher= asiaone |date= 14 June 2014 |accessdate= 2015-07-05 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20150519002535/http://yourhealth.asiaone.com/content/spore-national-gymnast-gruelling-schedule-keeps-her-shape |archive-date= 19 May 2015 |url-status= live |df= dmy-all }}\n</ref><ref>{{cite web |url= http://news.asiaone.com/News/Latest+News/Sports/Story/A1Story20130318-409387.html |title= Gymnastics hope for monetary boost |website= [[The New Paper]] |publisher= asiaone |date= 19 March 2013 |accessdate= 2015-07-05 |url-status= dead |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20160304093036/http://news.asiaone.com/News/Latest+News/Sports/Story/A1Story20130318-409387.html |archivedate= 4 March 2016 |df= dmy-all }}</ref> Similarly, the 4,200-seat Bishan Stadium<ref name=\"renamed_from_20141025_on_20150705203415\">\n{{cite web|url= http://news.asiaone.com/news/sports/football-bishan-back|title= Football: Bishan as back-up?|website= [[The New Paper]]|publisher= asiaone|date= 25 October 2014|accessdate= 2015-07-05|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20190204122431/http://news.asiaone.com/news/sports/football-bishan-back|archive-date= 4 February 2019|url-status= live|df= dmy-all}}\n</ref> has hosted the [[Sport of athletics|athletics]] and [[association football|football]] competitions at the 2010 Youth Olympic Games and the 2015 SEA Games respectively.<ref name=\"yog\" /><ref name=\"st20150528\" />\n\nBishan Stadium is the home of the [[Home United FC|Home United Football Club]], a professional football club that plays in Singapore's [[S.League]].<ref name=\"st20150528\" />\n\nOpened in 2008, the Bishan Active park also offers sporting facilities to the residents of Bishan.<ref name=\"asiaone20080824\">{{cite web |url=http://news.asiaone.com/News/AsiaOne+News/Singapore/Story/A1Story20080825-83994.html |title=$1.8 mil sports hub opens in Bishan |website=[[The Straits Times]] |publisher=asiaone |date=24 August 2008 |accessdate=2015-07-05 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160315090604/http://news.asiaone.com/News/AsiaOne+News/Singapore/Story/A1Story20080825-83994.html |archivedate=15 March 2016 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> This 24,000 [[square metres]] park houses facilities such as a [[roller blading]] track, [[basketball]] courts and a [[beach volleyball]] court, augmenting the facilities found at the Bishan Sports Centre.<ref name=\"asiaone20080824\" /><ref>\n{{cite web  |title= $1.7 Million  Dollar  Sports  Venue to Promote Healthy Lifestyle in Bishan-Toa Payoh GRC  |url= http://www.btptc.org.sg/E-news/NewsArticles/Articles/BISHANActive.pdf  |website= Bishan-Toa Payoh Town Council  |date= 7 January 2004  |accessdate= 2015-07-05  |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20150923194930/http://www.btptc.org.sg/E-news/NewsArticles/Articles/BISHANActive.pdf  |archive-date= 23 September 2015  |url-status= live  |df= dmy-all  }}\n</ref>\n\n==Infrastructure==\n\n===Transport===\n{{see also| Bishan MRT station| Bishan Bus Interchange}}\nBishan is connected by road to the rest of Singapore via the [[Central Expressway, Singapore|Central Expressway]], a major expressway connecting Northern parts of Singapore with its city centre.<ref name=\"streetdirectory\" /> In addition it has its own [[Mass Rapid Transit (Singapore)|Mass Rapid Transit]] (MRT) station, the [[Bishan MRT station]], which is an interchange station on both the [[North South MRT Line|North South Line]] and [[Circle MRT Line|Circle Line]].<ref name=\"streetdirectory\" /> Bishan also has a [[Bishan Bus Interchange|bus interchange]] that provides bus services to other parts of Singapore (such as Changi and Punggol).<ref name=\"sbs\" /> There are also feeder bus services that operate within the neighbourhood.<ref name=\"sbs\">\n{{cite web |url=http://www.sbstransit.com.sg/transport/trpt_bus_inter.aspx#bn |title=SBS Interchanges and Terminals |website=[[SBS Transit|4=SBS Transit Ltd.]] |accessdate=2015-06-28 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150626220425/http://www.sbstransit.com.sg/transport/trpt_bus_inter.aspx#bn#bn |archive-date=26 June 2015 |url-status=live |df=dmy-all }}\n</ref>\n\nThe Kallang Park Connector, which begins in Bishan, provides a cycling route between Bishan and the Central Business District along the [[Kallang River]]. This 10&nbsp;km route is the first [[park connector]] constructed in Singapore.<ref name=\"asiaone20150701\">\n{{cite web |url=http://news.asiaone.com/news/singapore/bishan-cbd-bicycle |title=Bishan to CBD on a bicycle? |website=[[The Straits Times]] |publisher=asiaone |date=2015-07-01 |accessdate=2015-07-04 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150704020311/http://news.asiaone.com/news/singapore/bishan-cbd-bicycle |archive-date=4 July 2015 |url-status=live |df=dmy-all }}\n</ref>\n\n[[Bright Hill MRT station]], a station on the upcoming [[Thomson-East Coast MRT Line]], will link the [[Sin Ming]] area of Bishan with the Central Business District of Singapore.<ref name=\"asiaone20120829\">{{cite web |url=http://transport.asiaone.com/news/transport/story/new-thomson-mrt-line-open-2019 |title=New Thomson MRT line to open in 2019 |website=Asiaone |date=2012-08-29 |accessdate=2015-08-02 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151125233756/http://transport.asiaone.com/news/transport/story/new-thomson-mrt-line-open-2019 |archivedate=25 November 2015 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\n=== Shopping centres ===\nBishan currently has 7 shopping centres.\n\n*The [[Junction 8 Shopping Centre]], run by [[CapitaLand]], is situated at Bishan Central near the [[Bishan MRT station]] and [[Bishan Bus Interchange]].\n*The Bishan North Shopping Mall is a non-airconditioned complex of shops that specialise in the sale of day-to-day products. It features a wet market. Contrary to its name, it is not a shopping mall.\n*[[Thomson Plaza]] is located on [[Upper Thomson Road]].\n*Thomson V One and Two is a residential complex that comes with a mall featuring shoebox sized retail units on the ground floor and basements.\n*Thomson Imperial Court and Sin Ming Plaza, are residential complexes with retail outlets on the ground floor and basement.\n*Midview City\nAn industrial shopping complex located at Sin Ming.\n\n===Bishan-Ang Mo Kio Park===\n{{Main| Bishan-Ang Mo Kio Park}}\n[[File:Singapore Bishan Park.jpeg|thumb|right|250px|The Kallang River at Bishan-Ang Mo Kio Park]]\n\nThe [[riverine]] Bishan-Ang Mo Kio Park, is situated near the boundary line between Bishan and [[Ang Mo Kio]], located along the stretch of Ang Mo Kio Avenue 1. The [[Kallang River]] which channels through the middle of the park, can be crossed via a number of foot bridges and stepping stones. The park also spots ponds and fishing spots, and serves residents from both new towns.\n\nBishan Park 1 is smaller in area than Bishan Park 2, and is about 1.7&nbsp;km in length from end to end. A park-spa has been newly built in this park. This park primarily serves walkers in the morning. Bishan Park 1 is more accessible than Bishan Park 2.\n\nBishan Park 2 sprawls over a larger area than Bishan Park 1 but is only about 1.1&nbsp;km in length from end to end.\n\n==Education==\nIn 1936, the Kwong Wai Siew Peck San Theng foundation established a village school in the former Kampong San Teng to provide free education to the farming families living in the vicinity.<ref name=\"pecksanthenghistory\">{{cite web |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20150717044407/http://www.pecksantheng.com/index.php/history |archivedate= 2015-07-17 |url= http://www.pecksantheng.com/index.php/history |title= Kwong Wai Siew Peck San Theng: History |website = Kwong Wai Siew Peck San Theng Foundation |language= Chinese | date = 2012 |accessdate= 2015-07-17}}</ref> The Kwong Wai Shiu Peck San Theng School (\u5e7f\u60e0\u8087\u78a7\u5c71\u4ead\u5b66\u6821) was initially housed on the foundation's temple premises.<ref name=\"straitstimes19810107\" /> Starting with 60 students, the school gradually expanded to the point where it started an afternoon session to cater to the demand.<ref name=\"straitstimes19810107\">{{cite news |author=Wong, Grace |title= Educator recalls old days |newspaper=[[The Straits Times]] |location= Singapore |date= 7 January 1981 }}</ref> The school had to stop classes during the [[Japanese occupation of Singapore]] but lessons soon resumed in 1945.<ref name=\"pecksanthenghistory\" /> In 1957, the school shifted into a new school compound situated at the entrance of a cemetery compound near [[Upper Thomson]].<ref name=\"straitstimes19810107\" /> The new school compound had 6 classrooms and could cater to 450 students in two school sessions.<ref name=\"pecksanthenghistory\" /> The Kwong Wai Shiu Peck San Theng School was also integrated into [[Education in Singapore|Singapore's mainstream education system]] that year.<ref name=\"pecksanthenghistory\" /> In 1981, due to changes in Singapore's national educational policy, governmental funding to the school was halted and the Kwong Wai Shiu Peck San Theng School soon closed down.<ref name=\"pecksanthenghistory\" />\n\nIn addition, the current site of the Amtech Building located at Sin Ming Road also used to house another school known as Shin Min Public School (\u6de1\u7533\u5f8b\u516c\u7acb\u65b0\u6c11\u5b66\u6821) from 1945 to 1986, which had closed due to low enrollment.<ref name=\"Shin Min Public School\">\n{{cite web|url=http://eresources.nlb.gov.sg/printheritage/image.aspx?id=4b1cbf5c-f264-409f-be58-f7aa8f47b2f8|title=Shin Min Public School in Thomson, circa 1971|publisher=NLB|access-date=8 January 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304101618/http://eresources.nlb.gov.sg/printheritage/image.aspx?id=4b1cbf5c-f264-409f-be58-f7aa8f47b2f8|archive-date=4 March 2016|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}\n</ref>\n\n[[File:Aerial view of the Year 1\u20134 campus, Raffles Institution (Secondary), Singapore - 20100516.jpg|thumb|right|250px|An aerial view of the Bishan campus of [[Raffles Institution]]]]\n\nSince its redevelopment in the 1980s, Bishan has become home to several educational institutions. According to the [[Ministry of Education, Singapore|Ministry of Education]], there are four [[primary schools]]<ref name=\"moe1\">\n{{cite web |url= http://www.moe.gov.sg/education/admissions/primary-one-registration/listing-by-planning-area/ |title= List of Primary Schools by Planning Area |website= Ministry of Education, Singapore |accessdate= 2015-06-28 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20150630183157/http://www.moe.gov.sg/education/admissions/primary-one-registration/listing-by-planning-area/ |archive-date= 30 June 2015 |url-status= live |df= dmy-all }}\n</ref> and seven [[Secondary education in Singapore|secondary schools]]<ref name=\"moe2\">{{cite web |url=http://www.moe.gov.sg/education/admissions/secondary-one-posting/files/schools-by-area.pdf |title=Key Information on Schools |website=Ministry of Education, Singapore |accessdate=2015-06-28 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130903001727/http://www.moe.gov.sg/education/admissions/secondary-one-posting/files/schools-by-area.pdf |archivedate=3 September 2013 |df=dmy }}</ref> that are located within Bishan. [[Raffles Institution]], one of the oldest educational institutions in Singapore, has been located in Bishan since 1990.<ref name=\"ri\">\n{{cite web |url= http://eresources.nlb.gov.sg/infopedia/articles/SIP_17_2004-12-21.html |title= Raffles Institution on Infopedia |website= National Library Board, Singapore |date= 2004-12-21 |accessdate= 2015-08-02 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20150825040844/http://eresources.nlb.gov.sg/infopedia/articles/SIP_17_2004-12-21.html |archive-date= 25 August 2015 |url-status= live |df= dmy-all }}\n</ref> This campus houses both of the institution's secondary and high school sections.<ref name=\"ri\" /> There are rumours that [[Raffles Girls' School (Secondary)|Raffles Girls' School]] will also relocate to the area in the near future.<ref>\n{{Cite web|title = Filiae Melioris \u00c6vi: Meeting the Sons of Singapore|url = http://rafflespress.com/2012/09/02/filiae-melioris-aevi-meeting-the-sons-of-singapore/|website = Raffles Press|accessdate = 2015-11-25|archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20151125232740/http://rafflespress.com/2012/09/02/filiae-melioris-aevi-meeting-the-sons-of-singapore/|archive-date = 25 November 2015|url-status = live|df = dmy-all}}\n</ref> Other notable schools located in Bishan include [[Ai Tong School]], a primary school founded by Chinese pioneers in 1912,<ref name=\"moe4\">{{cite web |url= http://www.moe.gov.sg/media/speeches/2007/sp20071012_print.htm |title= Speech by Lui Tuck Yew, Minister of State, Ministry of Education, at Ai Tong School's 95th Anniversary Celebration Dinner |website= Ministry of Education, Singapore |date= 2007-10-12 |accessdate= 2015-08-02 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20151125210233/http://www.moe.gov.sg/media/speeches/2007/sp20071012_print.htm |archive-date= 25 November 2015 |url-status= dead |df= dmy-all }}</ref> and [[Catholic High School, Singapore|Catholic High School]], a [[Special Assistance Plan]] school that names Singapore Prime Minister [[Lee Hsien Loong]] as one of its alumni.<ref name=\"straitstimes19850821\">{{cite news |author=Wong, Grace |title= Educator recalls old days |newspaper=[[The Straits Times]] |location= Singapore |date= 21 August 1985 }}</ref>\n\nThe prominent schools of Bishan are namely [[Guangyang Secondary School]], Guangyang Primary School, [[Kuo Chuan Presbyterian Secondary School]] and Kuo Chuan Presbyterian Primary School.\n\nIn addition, at Bishan North, there are [[Whitley Secondary School]] of Bishan Street 24, Peirce Secondary School and [[Bishan Park Secondary School]], both of which are located at Sin Ming Ave.\n\nDespite bearing the name Peirce Secondary School, the school was actually a subordinate branch of [[Bishan Park Secondary School]] when it first started operating off the latter's campus in 1994.<ref name=\"Peirce Secondary School\">\n{{cite web|url=http://www.peircesec.moe.edu.sg/about-us/history/|title=History|publisher=MOE|access-date=4 March 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160502044914/http://www.peircesec.moe.edu.sg/about-us/history/|archive-date=2 May 2016|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}\n</ref>\n\nThe [[Ministry of Education, Singapore|Ministry of Education]] announced [[Bishan Park Secondary School]] as one of the schools to be affected by the merger programme. As a result, it is to be absorbed by Peirce Secondary School in 2018.<ref name=\"22 secondary schools to merge over next 2 years due to falling demand\">\n{{cite web|url=http://www.channelnewsasia.com/mobile/singapore/22-secondary-schools-to/2572566.html|title=To merge in January 2018|publisher=CNA|access-date=4 March 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160306215855/http://www.channelnewsasia.com/mobile/singapore/22-secondary-schools-to/2572566.html|archive-date=6 March 2016|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}\n</ref>\n\nThe Bishan campus of the [[Institute of Technical Education]] (ITE) was established in 1994 as part of the government's plan to revamp Singapore's [[vocational education]] system.<ref name=\"ite\">\n{{cite web |url= http://eresources.nlb.gov.sg/infopedia/articles/SIP_1835_2011-08-31.html |title= Institute of Technical Education on Infopedia |website= National Library Board, Singapore |date= 2011-08-31 |accessdate= 2015-08-02 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20150919035321/http://eresources.nlb.gov.sg/infopedia/articles/SIP_1835_2011-08-31.html |archive-date= 19 September 2015 |url-status= live |df= dmy-all }}\n</ref> It provided vocational courses in subjects such as [[accountancy]] and [[business]].<ref>{{cite web |url= https://www.ite.edu.sg/wps/wcm/connect/5c103e80450a6e16bf45bfc07d13dcc3/Location.pdf?MOD=AJPERES |title= Location of ITE Colleges |website = Institute of Technical Education | date = 2010 |accessdate= 2015-08-02}}</ref> In 2005, this campus became part of [[ITE College Central]] during a major revamp of the ITE system.<ref name=\"ite\" /> This campus was subsequently closed in 2012 and relocated to the new ITE College Central mega-campus in [[Ang Mo Kio]].<ref name=\"asiaone20121031\">{{cite news |author= Ng, Gwendolyn |url= http://news.asiaone.com/News/Latest+News/Edvantage/Story/A1Story20121031-380533.html |title= New mega campus set to change public's view of ITE |newspaper= [[my paper]] |publisher= Asiaone |location= Singapore |date= 2012-10-31 |accessdate= 2015-08-02 |url-status= dead |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20160322020822/http://news.asiaone.com/News/Latest+News/Edvantage/Story/A1Story20121031-380533.html |archivedate= 22 March 2016 |df= dmy-all }}</ref> The old facilities of ITE Bishan currently serve as a temporary holding site for schools which are undergoing renovation.<ref name=\"asiaone20150528\">{{cite news |author=Lee, Pearl |url= http://news.asiaone.com/news/education/moe-mulling-over-bishan-interim-jc-site |title= MOE mulling over Bishan interim JC site |newspaper=[[The Straits Times]] |publisher= Asiaone |location= Singapore |date= 28 May 2015 |accessdate= 2015-08-02 }}</ref>\n\nIn addition to mainstream schools, a campus of the [[Ministry of Education Language Centre]] (MOELC), where students get to learn additional foreign languages such as [[French language|French]] and [[German language|German]],<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.moe.gov.sg/media/press/2012/05/moe-language-centre-to-offer-s.php |title= MOE Language Centre to Offer Spanish as a Third Language from January 2014 |date= 26 May 2012 |accessdate= 2015-07-17 |url-status= dead |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20150720220627/http://www.moe.gov.sg/media/press/2012/05/moe-language-centre-to-offer-s.php |archivedate= 20 July 2015 |df= dmy-all }}</ref> is located in Bishan.<ref name=\"education\" /> The Singapore branches of the [[Girl Guides Singapore|Girl Guides Association]] and the [[The Singapore Scout Association|Scouts Association]] are also headquartered in Bishan.<ref name=\"education\"/>\n\nIt was announced that a new school named [[Eunoia Junior College]] is expected to be completed at the site of former Nature Park Golf Driving Range located at Sin Ming Avenue by late 2019.<ref name=\"Eunoia Junior College\">\n{{cite web|url=http://www.channelnewsasia.com/mobile/singapore/new-junior-college-to-be/2384372.html|title=New Junior College to be named Eunoia JC|publisher=Channel News Asia|access-date=12 January 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160102200435/http://www.channelnewsasia.com/mobile/singapore/new-junior-college-to-be/2384372.html|archive-date=2 January 2016|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}\n</ref>\n\nOther than schools ranging from primary to tertiary, there are also nurseries and kindergartens scattered across Bishan estate.\n\n==Housing==\n[[File:Bishan-SG.JPG|thumb|right|250px|Housing estate in Bishan]]\nThe town is a mixture of three, four and five-room [[Housing Development Board|HDB]] flats. The majority of the flats are four-room-ed, with a few being five and three. Some has balconies. Some are penthouse mansionettes. Block numbers starting with 1 as the first digit, are generally smaller and more connected with the town center. Blocks numbers with 2 as the first digit, are more spread out and generally larger in size. However, even blocks numbers starting with 2 are further categorised;25_ tend to be the largest flats in the whole estate, with flat sizes ranging from 1650sq feet to 1700sq feet, one of the largest HDB flats in Singapore. Other numbers tend to be smaller and are usually from 1300sq feet to 1500sq feet. Sin Ming Ville (Block 22-26) is excluded from this category.\n\nThere are also various condominiums in Bishan including the Sky Habitat, Clover by the Park and Country Grandeur.\n\nAs is with [[Serangoon New Town]], it was built in an area with a large extent of pre-existing private housing, resulting in a disjointed town layout. The oldest public housing blocks were located around [[Upper Thomson]] as housing for the surrounding industrial estate. When the area was designated as a new town, the main housing area was built in the vicinity of [[Bishan MRT station]], with neighbourhoods built in Bishan North and Shunfu. Newer blocks were also built in Upper Thomson, while the old blocks were refurbished.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Commons category|Bishan}}\n* [http://www.btptc.org.sg/ Bishan-Toa Payoh Town Council]\n\n{{Places in Singapore}}\n\n[[Category:Bishan, Singapore| ]]\n[[Category:Places in Singapore]]\n[[Category:Hills of Singapore]]\n[[Category:Hakka culture in Singapore]]\n[[Category:New towns started in the 1980s]]\n", "name_user": "Jobelasie", "label": "safe", "comment": "updated dwelling units", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bishan,_Singapore"}
